Forcasts and Predictions Course Project¶

Project Description

The gym chain Model Fitness is developing a customer interaction strategy based on analytical data.

One of the most common problems gyms and other services face is customer churn. How do you know if a customer is no longer with you? You can calculate churn based on people who get rid of their accounts or don't renew their contracts. However, sometimes it's not obvious that a client has left: they may walk out on tiptoes.

For a gym, it makes sense to say a customer has left if they don't come for a month. Of course, it's possible they're in Cancun and will resume their visits when they return, but's that's not a typical case. Usually, if a customer joins, comes a few times, then disappears, they're unlikely to come back.

In order to fight churn, Model Fitness has digitized a number of its customer profiles.

Tasks

  • Analyze the customer profiles and come up with a customer retention strategy.
    • Learn to predict the probability of churn (for the upcoming month) for each customer
    • Draw up typical user portraits: select the most outstanding groups and describe their main features
    • Analyze the factors that impact churn most
    • Draw basic conclusions and develop recommendations on how to improve customer service:
      • Identify target groups
      • Suggest measures to cut churn
      • Describe any other patterns you see with respect to interaction with customers

Important things to consider

Description of the data

  • file path: /datasets/gym_churn_us.csv
  • Model Fitness' csv contains data on chrun for a given month and information on the month preceding it and contains:
    • User data for the preceding month
      • 'gender'
      • 'Near_Location' whether the user lives or works in the neighborhood where the gym is located
      • 'Partner' whether the user is an employee of a partner company (the gym has partner companies whose employees get discounts; in those cases the gym stores information on customers' employers)
      • Promo_friends whether the user originally signed up through a "bring a friend" offer (they used a friend's promo code when paying for their first membership)
      • 'Phone' whether the user provided their phone number
      • 'Age'
      • 'Lifetime' the time (in months) since the customer first came to the gym
    • Data from the log of visits and purchases and data on current membership status
      • 'Contract_period' 1 month, 3 months, 6 months, or 1 year
      • 'Month_to_end_contract' the months remaining until the contract expires
      • 'Group_visits' whether the user takes part in group sessions
      • 'Avg_class_frequency_total' average frequency of visits per week over the customer's lifetime
      • 'Avg_class_frequency_current_month' average frequency of visits per week over the preceding month
      • 'Avg_additional_charges_total' the total amount of money spent on other gym services: cafe, athletic goods, cosmetics, massages, etc.

def plot_a_histogram(column):
    plt.figure(figsize = (12, 6))
#     plt.hist(gym_data_active[column], label = 'active', alpha = 0.7)
#     plt.hist(gym_data_churned[column], label = 'churned', alpha = 0.7)

    sns.distplot(gym_data_churned[column], label = 'churned')
    plt.title('{} distribution'.format(column), size = 15)
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(column), size = 15)
#     plt.ylabel('number of clients', size = 15) # use with plt.hist()

    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

def plot_a_bargraph(column, xticks = ['False', 'True']):
    table = gym_data.pivot_table(index = column, columns = 'churn', values = 'age', aggfunc = 'count')
    graph = table.plot(kind = 'bar')
    plt.title('{} feature status distribution'.format(column), size = 15)
    graph.set_xticklabels(xticks, rotation = 0)
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(column), size = 15)
    plt.ylabel('number of clients', size = 15)
    plt.legend(['active', 'churned'])
    plt.show()

  • The other half of active clients have 6 or 12 months left on their contracts

  • Most churned clients maintained a contract for 3 months or less

  • Most active clients maintained a contract for 8 months or less

  • Most churned clients visited the gym on average 1 - 2 days per week during their entire contract lifetime

  • Most active clients visit the gym on average 1 - 3 days per week during their entire contract lifetime

  • For the current month most churned clients visited the gym on average 0 - 2 days per week

  • For the current month, most active clients visited the gym on average 0 - 4 days per week

  • Active and Churned clients are evenly distributed among gender 0 and 1 in this data set

  • There are more clients located near gyms and most of them have active status.

  • The number of clients who are active vs churned not near a gym are about the same

  • There is about equal active clients not from and from partner employers, however clients from partners have less churn

  • Clients with a friend promo code have churned less, but there are also fewer of clients witha frined promo code vs with out

  • The number of clients with out a friend promo code that have churned equal about half of those who are active

    • maybe exercising with a friend keeps you motivated

  • There are many more active clients who have supplied their phone number, however the churn is a bit high - a little less than half of active

    • maybe the gym sends them reminders to visit

  • There are very few clients in this data set who have not supplied their phone number

  • Clients who dont participate in group classes are more likely to churn than those who do, however in this data set, there are more clients who do not attend group classes

  • Clients with a 1 month contract are more likely to churn compared to those with 6 or 12 month contracts, these churn numbers are very low

Reviewer's comment Very good! You studied feature distributions in the two groups and made some interesting observations!

Step 3 Build a model to predict user churn¶

Goal

  • Build a binary classification model for customers where the target feature is the user's leaving next month.

Plan of Action

  • Logistic Regression data prep
    • Remove featues with multicolinearity - must be done by hand for Logistic Regression models
    • Random Forest models are not affected by mulitcolinearity:
      • Random Forest uses bootstrap sampling and feature sampling, i.e row sampling and column sampling. Therefore Random Forest is not affected by multicollinearity that much since it is picking different set of features for different models and of course every model sees a different set of data points.
  • Divide the data into features (the X matrix) and a target variable (y)
  • 3.a Divide the data into train and validation sets using the train_test_split() function
  • 3.b Train the model on the train set with two methods:
    • 3.b.1 Logisitc Regression use the Lasso() model to account for multicolinearity
    • 3.b.2 Random Forest
  • 3.c Evaluate accuracy, precision, and recall for both models using the validation data. Use them to compare the models.
  • Conclusion: Which model gave better results?

Logistic Regression data prep

Remove featues with multicolinearity - must be done by hand for Logistic Regression models

  • Test two versions

      • avg_class_frequency_total, this leaves avg_class_frequency_total_current_month
      • contract_period_1 and contract_period_12, this leaves month_to_end_contract
    • Version 2: Remove the following two features:

  • 3.b The models (logistic regression V1 & V2 and Random Forest) were trained on the train sets

      • Precision: 0.80
      • Recall: 0.79
    • Logistic Regression V2 Stats (2 features removed)
      • Accuracy: 0.90
      • Precision: 0.79
      • Recall: 0.80
    • Random Forest Stats
      • Accuracy: 0.93
      • Precision: 0.85
      • Recall: 0.85
    • The Random Forest Model fits the best
      • It has the the highest accuracy, precision, and reacall
  • Accuracy: share of accurate predictions among all predictions - works best when the classes are balanced i.e. the objects are distributed almost evenly between the classes (50/50)
    • closer to 100% the better
  • Precision: share of predictions in class 1 are true i.e. the correct answers only in the target class
    • closer to 1 the better
  • Recall: the number of real calls 1 objects discovered in the model
    • colser to 1 the better
Reviewer's comment The models were trained and evaluated correctly. Conclusions look good.

def num_data_hist_plot(cluster_num, column, x_label):
    cluster_query_active = clustered_active[clustered_active['cluster'] == cluster_num]
    cluster_query_churned = clustered_churned[clustered_churned['cluster'] == cluster_num]
    sns.distplot(cluster_query_active[column], label = 'active')
    sns.distplot(cluster_query_churned[column], label = 'churned')
#     plt.hist(cluster_query_active[column], label = 'active', alpha = 0.7)
#     plt.hist(cluster_query_churned[column], label = 'churned', alpha = 0.7)
    plt.title('{} distribution for cluster {}'.format(column, cluster_num), size = 15)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, size = 15)
#     plt.ylabel('number of clients', size = 15) # use with plt.hist()
    plt.ylabel('frequency', size = 15) # use with sns.distplot()
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Step 5. Come up with conclusions and basic recommendations on working with customers¶

Conclusions

  • The data was processed and analyzed (EDA)
  • 2 models were used tested to forecast churn
    • Random Forest model was determined to be the best way to forecast churn
      • Accuracy: 0.93
      • Precision: 0.85
      • Recall: 0.85
  • 5 clusters were created as profiles for the client features
  • Clients likely to churn:
    • have a 1 month contract or 1 month left on their contract
    • visit the gym less than 2 times per week
    • are less likely:
      • to be an employee of a partner employer
      • to have a friend promo code
      • to attend group classes

Recommendations

  • Essentially make it as easy as possible for a client to go to the gym and know what to do
  • Especially engage with clients who have a 1 month contract or 1 month left on their contract
    • offer a 30 minute introduction to the gym and its resources for new clients
  • However to decrease effort aim to engage all clients at some level, because all clients will eventually have 1 month left on their contract
    • Encourage them to visit more than 2 times per week and to participate in group classes
    • Offer general workout plans for beginners, intermediate, and seasoned clients with instuctions on how to do the exercises, include group classes and additional services to support their health and fitness goals
    • Offer a complimentary smoothie if they provide their phone number
      • Use their phone number to send reminders to go to the gym, attend a class, or to promote special services
    • Continue to maintain and create relationships with current and future partner employers
    • Continue to offer friend promo code
    • Offer discounts on longer contract lenghts to encourage sign up
Reviewer's comment Excellent summary! Recommendations make sense and are based on the previous research. Well done!
